U.S. Gulf Oil Premiums Strengthen as Brent-WTI Spread Widens

-- B y   A a r o n   C l a r k
-- 
2011-07-18T17:02:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-18/u-s-gulf-oil-premiums-strengthen-as-brent-wti-spread-widens.html
Crude oil premiums in the U.S. Gulf
strengthened as the spread widened between benchmark West Texas
Intermediate Brent.  The gap increased 99 cents to $20.65 a barrel as of 12:47
p.m. in  New York . The spread settled at a record high of $22.63
a barrel July 14.  When Brent gains versus WTI, it strengthens the value of
low-sulfur U.S. grades that compete with West African oil priced
against the European benchmark.  Light Louisiana Sweet’s premium rose 25 cents to $19.50 a
barrel over WTI as of 11:49 a.m. in New York, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg. Heavy Louisiana Sweet’s premium was
unchanged at $23.25 a barrel over the benchmark.  Among sour, or high-sulfur, grades, the premiums for Mars
Blend and Poseidon increased 95 cents to $17.70.  Southern Green Canyon advanced $1 to $16.75 a barrel over
WTI, while West Texas Sour’s discount narrowed 5 cents to 70
cents. Thunder Horse’s premium added 75 cents to $23.25.  The premium for Syncrude was unchanged at $9.50. Syncrude
is a light, low-sulfur synthetic oil derived from the tar sands
in  Alberta .  The discount for Western Canada Select was unchanged at
$18.65 a barrel.  To contact the reporter on this story:
